Plenty of evidence for this already. Modelling suggests storms are getting "front-loaded" so they dump more rain at the very beginning of a downpour. That's why we're breaking rainfall intensity records. My back yard managed 50mm in 30min recently. That's heavier rain than most cyclones.



Author::::Henforthe
DateTime::::2016-03-09T21:08:55Z
This is exactly what we see when we look at the 'hyperthermals' in the geologic past. Spikes in greenhouse gases, probably originating in rare extreme volcanic events, tie in not only with a temperature hike and sea level rise, but also indicators in the sedimentary record that hint both at higher aridity and higher precipitation- sometimes in the same locations. So we should expect to see a more extreme, 'monsoon-style' precipitation regime across more of the world. 



